t: Psalm 77
To the chief Musician, to Jeduthun, A Psalm of Asaph.
I*p cried unto God with my voice, even unto God with my voice; and he gave ear unto me.
In*p the day of my trouble I sought the Lord: my sore ran in the night, and ceased not: my soul refused to be comforted.
I*p remembered God, and was troubled: I complained, and my spirit was overwhelmed. Selah.
Thou*p holdest mine eyes waking: I am so troubled that I cannot speak.
I*p have considered the days of old, the years of ancient times.
I*p call to remembrance my song in the night: I commune with mine own heart: and my spirit made diligent search.
Will*p the Lord cast off for ever? and will he be favourable no more?
Is*p his mercy clean gone for ever? doth his promise fail for evermore?
Hath*p God forgotten to be gracious? hath he in anger shut up his tender mercies? Selah.
And*p I said, This is my infirmity: but I will remember the years of the right hand of the most High.
I*p will remember the works of the Lord:*s surely I will remember thy wonders of old.
I*p will meditate also of all thy work, and talk of thy doings.
Thy*p way, O God, is in the sanctuary: who is so great a God as our God?
Thou*p art the God that doest wonders: thou hast declared thy strength among the people.
Thou*p hast with thine arm redeemed thy people, the sons of Jacob and Joseph. Selah.
The*p waters saw thee, O God, the waters saw thee; they were afraid: the depths also were troubled.
The*p clouds poured out water: the skies sent out a sound: thine arrows also went abroad.
The*p voice of thy thunder was in the heaven: the lightnings lightened the world: the earth trembled and shook.
Thy*p way is in the sea, and thy path in the great waters, and thy footsteps are not known.
Thou*p leddest thy people like a flock by the hand of Moses and Aaron.
